    "summarizer": {
      "general_reader_takeaway": "This paper argues that when two nearly identical ringing signals overlap\u2014as can happen in gravitational waves from merging black holes\u2014it is more stable to describe them jointly around a shared \"carrier\" frequency than as two separate, independent signals. The review board found the core mathematical idea correct but classical, already well-known in signal processing under names like Prony's method and ESPRIT. A concrete numerical inconsistency in the figures, missing supporting derivations, and an irreproducible gravitational-wave application prevent full verification. The paper may offer useful conceptual framing for the gravitational-wave ringdown community, but it does not demonstrate that it outperforms existing methods.",
      "reviewer": "claude",
      "technical_takeaway": "The paper recasts the classical near-degenerate exponential ill-conditioning result (Prony/Vandermonde) into the Green-function language of gravitational-wave ringdown, proposing a carrier-plus-first-jet basis and a two-scale hierarchy governed by \u03b5 = |\u03b4|T and \u03b7 = |\u03b4|\u00b2T\u00b2. The algebraic reorganization of the two-pole block (Eqs. 1\u20134) is exact partial-fraction algebra; the conditioning contrast (Eq. 8) is demonstrated only along the real-splitting slice and is not extended to complex QNM splittings. A concrete arithmetic inconsistency in Fig. 2 (reported \u03ba = 0.400 vs. computed \u03b7\u00b7\u03c1 = 0.260 \u00d7 0.650 = 0.169, contradicting Eq. 13) was confirmed by all three reviewers. Supplemental Secs. A\u2013C cited for key derivations and coefficient-recovery tests are absent from the submission. The Kerr numerical section uses undefined terminology and omits mode labels, T_eff, perturbation model, and inverse-problem protocol, making it irreproducible. No noise or SNR model is provided, leaving the practical instability claim unquantified. No comparison to existing near-degenerate mode extraction methods (ESPRIT, SVD-regularized Prony) is made."
    }
